  "prompt": "I'm a US citizen and my boyfriend is Argentinean; if we get married in the US, how long will it take for him to be qualified to work in the US?",
  "response": "Okay, let's break down the timeline for your boyfriend to be authorized to work in the US after marrying you, a US citizen.\n\n**The General Process: Adjustment of Status**\n\nThe most common route for your boyfriend to get work authorization is through a process called \"Adjustment of Status\" (AOS).  This allows him to apply for a green card (lawful permanent residence) while he is already physically present in the United States. Since he's already in the US when you marry, he can begin this process.\n\n**Key Steps and Estimated Timelines (Keep in Mind These are Estimates!)**\n\n1.  **Marriage and Filing the Initial Petition (I-130 & I-485):**\n\n    *   **Immediately after marriage:** You, as the US citizen spouse, file Form I-130 (Petition for Alien Relative) to establish the familial relationship.  At the same time, he, as the beneficiary, files Form I-485 (Application to Register Permanent Residence or Adjust Status). Because he is the spouse of a US Citizen, he is considered an \"Immediate Relative\" and may apply for Adjustment of Status concurrent with the I-130, assuming he is otherwise eligible.\n    *   **Also file concurrently with the I-130 and I-485**: Form I-765 (Application for Employment Authorization Document or EAD) and Form I-131 (Application for Travel Document). This is crucial for getting work authorization.\n    *   **Timeline:** This filing happens as soon as possible after the marriage.\n    *   **Important:** Filing these forms correctly and with all required supporting documentation is critical. Missing documents or errors can cause delays or even denial.\n\n2.  **USCIS Processing (Receipt Notices, Biometrics, etc.):**\n\n    *   **Within 2-3 weeks:** You should receive receipt notices from USCIS (United States Citizenship and Immigration Services) confirming they received your applications.  These notices are very important.\n    *   **Within 4-8 weeks:** He will likely receive an appointment notice for biometrics (fingerprinting, photo, and signature).  Attending this appointment is mandatory.\n\n3.  **Employment Authorization Document (EAD) Approval:**\n\n    *   **This is the key to working!** After filing Form I-765, it typically takes **3-12 months** to receive the Employment Authorization Document (EAD) card.  The processing times vary depending on the USCIS service center handling the case and current backlogs.\n    *   **Important:** Processing times are estimates and can fluctuate. Check the USCIS website for the most up-to-date processing times for the specific service center handling the I-765.\n\n4.  **Interview (Potentially):**\n\n    *   USCIS may schedule an interview for the I-485 application. This isn't always required, especially for straightforward cases, but it's common.\n    *   **Timeline:** If an interview is required, it could be scheduled several months after the initial filing.\n    *   **Purpose:** The interview is to verify the information in the applications and ensure the marriage is legitimate (not solely for immigration purposes).\n\n5.  **Green Card Approval (I-485):**\n\n    *   After a successful interview (if required) and all background checks are completed, the I-485 application can be approved.\n    *   **Timeline:** This can take **6-36 months** from the initial filing, depending on the USCIS workload and the complexity of the case.  It can sometimes be approved before the interview.\n\n**So, to answer your question directly, your boyfriend could potentially be authorized to work in the US within approximately 3-12 months after filing the I-765 (Application for Employment Authorization Document).**\n\n**Important Considerations and Caveats:**\n\n*   **Eligibility:** He must be eligible to adjust status. This means he must have entered the US legally (e.g., with a valid visa or through the Visa Waiver Program), not have violated his immigration status (overstayed significantly or worked without authorization), and not have any other factors that would make him ineligible for a green card (criminal history, etc.). An overstay is usually forgiven because he is an immediate relative of a US Citizen.\n*   **USCIS Processing Times:** These are *estimates* only. USCIS processing times can change significantly due to workload, policy changes, and other factors. Always check the USCIS website for the most current processing times for each form (I-130, I-485, I-765).\n*   **Accuracy and Completeness:** It is *crucial* to file all forms accurately and with all required supporting documentation. Errors or missing information can cause significant delays.\n*   **\"Public Charge\" Rule:** USCIS will evaluate whether your boyfriend is likely to become a \"public charge\" (primarily dependent on government benefits). Having a job and the ability to support himself will be helpful in this regard.\n*   **Travel:**  While his I-485 is pending, it's generally *not* recommended that he leave the US without first obtaining Advance Parole (through Form I-131, filed concurrently with the I-485). Leaving without Advance Parole could be considered abandoning the application.\n*   **Legal Advice:** This information is for general guidance only and is not legal advice. It is *highly recommended* that you consult with an experienced US immigration attorney to discuss your specific situation and ensure you follow the correct procedures. An attorney can help you navigate the complexities of the immigration process, avoid potential pitfalls, and maximize your chances of success.\n\n**In summary:**\n\n1.  Marry in the US.\n2.  File I-130, I-485, I-765, and I-131 concurrently as soon as possible after the marriage.\n3.  Closely monitor USCIS processing times.\n4.  Consult with an immigration attorney for personalized legal advice.\n\nGood luck!\n",
